Clean and prepare data

split_row <- round(nrow(ds) * 0.9375)
train <- ds[1:split_row,]
test <- ds[(split_row+1):nrow(ds),]

Part1

model_arima<-auto.arima(train$ds)
summary(model_arima)
## Series: train$ds 
## ARIMA(3,0,1) with non-zero mean 
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1      ar2     ar3      ma1      mean
##       2.1202  -1.4478  0.2753  -0.9402  746.3552
## s.e.  0.0550   0.1029  0.0543   0.0181    7.7055
## 
## sigma^2 = 15246:  log likelihood = -2243.79
## AIC=4499.58   AICc=4499.82   BIC=4522.9
## 
## Training set error measures:
##                     ME    RMSE      MAE  MPE MAPE     MASE      ACF1
## Training set -1.923436 122.613 86.12517 -Inf  Inf 0.763902 0.0215028
models <- data.frame(p = integer(), q = integer(), AICc = numeric(), BIC = numeric(), stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
for (p in 0:3) {
  for (q in 0:3) {
    if (p == 0 && q == 0) next
    tryCatch({
      model <- Arima(train$ds, order = c(p, 0, q), method = "ML")
      models <- models %>% add_row(p = p, q = q, AICc = AICc(model), BIC = BIC(model))
    }, error = function(e) {})
  }
}

# find the best model based on AICc and BIC
best_AICc <- models %>% slice_min(AICc)
best_BIC <- models %>% slice_min(BIC)

Ans1 - Initial model is ARIMA(3,0,1) with non-zero mean. The above code optimized the values of p,d,q while repeatedly testing for AICc and BIC values and returned the most optimal model.

Part2

train$day_of_week <- wday(train$datetime, label = TRUE)
test$day_of_week <- wday(test$datetime, label = TRUE)

ts_train <- ts(train$ds, frequency = 24)

fit <- auto.arima(ts_train, seasonal = 168)

ts_test <- ts(test$ds[test$day_of_week == "Mon"], frequency = 24)

# generate forecasts using ARIMA model
forecast <- forecast(fit, h = length(ts_test))

plot(forecast, main = "ARIMA Forecast for Monday", ylab = "ds")

lines(ts_test, col = "blue")

legend("topleft", legend = c("Forecast", "Actual"), col = c("black", "blue"), lty = 1)

Ans2 - Above shows forecast for July 1, Monday using hourly data.
